Case Study - Bellabeat

Dino Dudic

2024-02-05

Introduction

This case study entails the analysis of publicly available data for Bellabeat Link to Kaggle Fitbit Dataset, a health-focused women tech company. The objective is to identify growth opportunities within the global smart device market.

Stakeholders

  • Urška Sršen: Co-founder and Chief Creative Officer.
  • Sando Mur: Co-founder and mathematician.
  • Bellabeat Marketing Analytics Team: The team of data analysts.

About the Company

Founded in 2013, Bellabeat is a tech-driven wellness company that empowers women with smart products designed to enhance their health and well-being. The company has experienced rapid growth through a combination of traditional and digital marketing strategies.

Data-Driven Recommendations

The analysis seeks to reveal trends in smart device usage, evaluate their relevance to Bellabeat customers, and leverage these insights to shape the company’s marketing strategy. This case study will conclude with data-driven recommendations that offer a strategic roadmap for Bellabeat’s future endeavors.

ASK

1.How does physical activity influence the quality and duration of sleep among our users?
2.What are the daily activity patterns of our users, and how do these relate to their engagement levels?
3.What percentage of our users meet the recommended guidelines for sleep duration, and which factors affect          their sleep quality?
4.Are there discernible trends in user engagement based on the frequency and intensity of device usage?

PREPARE

The analysis utilizes a Fitbit user data set from Mobius, available publicly on Kaggle. This data set includes de-identified data from thirty Fitbit users, detailing physical activity, heart rate, and sleep patterns. Uploaded to the Posit Cloud R environment, the data is in long format, suitable for detailed time series analysis.

However, the absence of demographic information in the data set introduces a potential sampling bias. Ethical considerations are addressed by the data set’s public domain status and user consent for data submission. The main limitation is the data set’s short time frame and limited sample size, which may impact the depth of insights derived. Despite these constraints, the data set offers valuable insights for understanding smart device usage patterns.

Data Cleaning and Standardization Process

In this section, the data cleaning and standardization process are addressed through the following steps:

  1. Inconsistencies in Timestamp Formats: Variations in timestamp formats were observed across different datasets.

  2. Standardization for Uniformity: To ensure a consistent date-time format for ease of manipulation and analysis, the as.POSIXct() function was applied to standardize all timestamp columns across datasets.

  3. Awareness of Merged Data: It was noted that certain datasets are composites, combining multiple data types. For example, the dailyActivity dataset incorporates data from dailySteps, dailyCalories, and dailyIntensities. Understanding the structure of these composite datasets is essential for accurate data processing and analysis.

Standardizing Timestamp Formats

# Standardizing timestamps across different datasets

# Daily Data

# Activity
dailyActivity$ActivityDate <- as.POSIXct(dailyActivity$ActivityDate, format="%m/%d/%Y", tz=Sys.timezone())
dailyActivity$date <- as.Date(format(dailyActivity$ActivityDate, format = "%Y-%m-%d"))
dailyActivity$ActivityDate <- NULL

# Sleep
dailySleep$SleepDay <- as.POSIXct(dailySleep$SleepDay, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone())

Data Cleaning

A function is defined to clean each data set, which carries out three essential actions:

  1. Removes rows with missing values.
  2. Eliminates duplicate entries.
  3. Trims white spaces in character columns for consistency and accuracy.

Defining the Data Cleaning Function

clean_dataset <- function(dataset) {
  # Checking for missing values
  dataset <- dataset[complete.cases(dataset), ]
  
  # Removing duplicate values
  dataset <- dataset[!duplicated(dataset), ]
  
  # Trim whitespaces in character columns only
  dataset <- dataset %>%
    mutate_if(is.character, str_trim)
  
  return(dataset)
}

Applying the Cleaning Function to Each Dataset

# Applying the cleaning function
dailyActivity <- clean_dataset(dailyActivity)
dailySleep <- clean_dataset(dailySleep)
weight <- clean_dataset(weight)
hourlyCalories <- clean_dataset(hourlyCalories)
hourlyIntensities <- clean_dataset(hourlyIntensities)
hourlySteps <- clean_dataset(hourlySteps)

Data Cleaning Note

Attempts to clean the ‘met’ and ‘heartrate’ data sets with the ‘clean_dataset’ function have resulted in crashes. These issues are likely due to the large size of these data sets and the computational limitations of the free version of posit.cloud.

As a result, the ‘heartrate’ and ‘met’ data sets will be processed separately using more resource-efficient methods or at a later stage when enhanced computing resources become available.

Please note that ‘heartrate’ and ‘met’ data sets are not cleaned at this stage due to the mentioned issues.

Categorize Users by Activity Frequency and Count the Number in Each Group

The code below categorizes users into “active” or “not active” based on their daily calorie burn and step count, then summarizes the total number of active days for each user. It assigns users to usage categories based on their activity frequency and calculates the number of users in each category.

dailyActivity$user_activity <- ifelse(dailyActivity$Calories == 0 | dailyActivity$TotalSteps == 0, "not active", "active")

active_days_summary <- dailyActivity %>%
  filter(user_activity == "active") %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarize(active_days_count = n()) %>%
  mutate(
    usage_category = case_when(
      active_days_count %in% 1:10 ~ "low usage",
      active_days_count %in% 11:20 ~ "moderate usage",
      active_days_count %in% 21:31 ~ "high usage",
      TRUE ~ "other"  # Catch-all for cases that don't match the above conditions
    )
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(usage_category) %>%
  summarize(count = n())

METs Data Processing

The exploration of METs (Metabolic Equivalent Task) data revealed interesting insights. Here are the key observations and steps taken during the analysis:

Suspicious Range of MET Values

The METs values displayed a suspicious range:

  • The minimum MET value was 0, which typically implies no activity (sleeping or resting).
  • The maximum MET value was 157, which is highly unusual. Typically, MET values range from 0 (resting) to around 20 or 30 for extremely vigorous activities. A value of 157 is likely an error or an outlier in the data.

Grouping MET Values by Hour

Calculating Average Resting Heart Rate

Rows in the wide table were filtered based on the criterion that all values between columns 3 and 7 for each row were non-zero. Subsequently, the average resting heart rate for each user was computed using these non-zero values.

# Calculate average resting heart rate
resting_heartrate <- wide_table_heartrate %>%
  filter(across(starts_with("3"), ~ . != 0) & 
         across(starts_with("4"), ~ . != 0) & 
         across(starts_with("5"), ~ . != 0) & 
         across(starts_with("6"), ~ . != 0) & 
         across(starts_with("7"), ~ . != 0)) %>%
  mutate(average_resting_heartrate = rowMeans(across(starts_with("3"):starts_with("7")), na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  dplyr::select(Id, average_resting_heartrate)

Categorization of Sleep Patterns

In order to gain insights into sleep health, users are categorized based on sleep latency and total sleep duration.

Categorizing Sleep Latency

We observed a minimum sleep latency of 3 minutes and a maximum of 309 minutes. Ideally, the average time to fall asleep should fall within the range of 10 to 20 minutes, as recommended by Jung et al. in their paper titled ‘Estimation of Sleep Onset Latency Based on the Blood Pressure Regulatory Reflex Mechanism’ (IEEE Journal of Biomedical and Health Informatics, May 2013, doi: 10.1109/JBHI.2013.2257816).

To align with these guidelines for healthy sleep latency, we categorized sleep latency into three groups:

  • Sleep latency less than 10 minutes
  • Sleep latency between 10 and 20 minutes
  • Sleep latency greater than 20 minutes
# Categorize sleep latency
sleep_latency <- avg_sleep_per_user %>%
  mutate(Category = case_when(
    avg_sleep_latency < 10 ~ "Sleep latency < 10 min",
    between(avg_sleep_latency, 10, 20) ~ "Sleep Latency: 10-20 min",
    avg_sleep_latency > 20 ~ "Sleep latency > 20 min",
    TRUE ~ "Undefined Category" # Capture outliers
  )) %>%
  group_by(Category) %>%
  summarise(Count = n_distinct(Id)) %>% 
  arrange(Count)

Categorizing Total Sleep Duration

Based on the research paper titled “Joint Consensus Statement of the American Academy of Sleep Medicine and Sleep Research Society on the Recommended Amount of Sleep for a Healthy Adult” by Watson et al. (2015), it is recommended that young adults should aim for a minimum of 7 hours of sleep per night to maintain good general health and overall physical and mental well-being. The study found that individuals who slept less than 7 hours were more likely to report poor general health and lower overall quality of life compared to those who slept 7 hours or more.

Therefore, it is advisable to categorize users into two groups based on their total sleep duration: 1. Less than 7 hours of sleep (<7 hours): This group may experience poor general health and lower overall physical and mental well-being. 2. Seven hours or more of sleep (≥7 hours): This group is expected to have better metrics in terms of general health and overall well-being relative to the <7 hours total sleep group.

These recommendations are based on the findings and consensus outlined in the research paper by Watson et al. (2015).

Reference: Watson NF, Badr MS, Belenky G, Bliwise DL, Buxton OM, Buysse D, Dinges DF, Gangwisch J, Grandner MA, Kushida C, Malhotra RK, Martin JL, Patel SR, Quan SF, Tasali E. Joint Consensus Statement of the American Academy of Sleep Medicine and Sleep Research Society on the Recommended Amount of Sleep for a Healthy Adult: Methodology and Discussion. J Clin Sleep Med. 2015 Aug 15;11(8):931-52. doi: 10.5664/jcsm.4950. PMID: 26235159; PMCID: PMC4513271.

ANALYZE

Investigation of Activity Influence on Sleep Quality

The subsequent analysis is focused on examining the influence of physical activity on sleep quality. This exploration will be carried out through regression models, with the objective of testing the relationship between activity levels and sleep patterns.

Hypothesis Development

The hypothesis is centered on the notion that physical activity significantly affects both the total amount of sleep and sleep latency. The expected outcomes are as follows:

  1. Increased Physical Activity: An increase in active minutes and total steps should correlate with reduced sleep latency and an increase in the total amount of sleep.
  2. Increased Sedentariness: More sedentary minutes are expected to correlate with increased sleep latency and a decrease in the total amount of sleep.

Research Methodology

The approach will involve constructing regression models to examine:

  • Active Minutes and Total Steps: These variables will be used as indicators of physical activity.
  • Sedentary Minutes: This will represent inactivity levels.

The effect of these variables will be assessed on:

  • Total Amount of Sleep
  • Sleep Latency

These models aim to quantify the relationship between activity levels and sleep patterns.

Anticipated Outcomes and Implementation

  • Model Analysis: If the regression models show significant correlations with good model fit, it would imply a strong relationship between activity levels and sleep quality.
  • App Integration: Successful results can be integrated into the app. This could include sending motivational messages or setting personalized activity goals for users to improve their sleep quality.
  • Guidance and Goal Setting: The app could suggest daily activity goals, providing users with specific targets and advice on achieving optimal sleep.

Preparing for Regression Analysis

In the following sections, an exploration will be undertaken into the construction and analysis of these regression models. The process will involve:

  1. Data Preparation: Merging and preparing the activity and sleep data for analysis.
  2. Regression Model Construction: Building and fine-tuning models for each variable.
  3. Results Interpretation: Analyzing and interpreting the findings to draw meaningful conclusions.

The objective of this analysis is to offer actionable insights that can assist users in enhancing their sleep quality by means of customized physical activity recommendations.

Regression Models Summary

Model 1: sleep_latency ~ TotalSteps

  • R-squared: -0.001558
  • Significance: Insignificant Coefficient (p-value = 0.547).
  • Assumption Violations:
    • Normality of Residuals: Histogram indicates a departure from normality.

Model 2: TotalMinutesAsleep ~ TotalSteps

  • R-squared: 0.03387

  • Assumption Violations:

    • Homoscedasticity: Evidence of heteroscedasticity (Breusch-Pagan test).
    • Independence of Residuals: Strong evidence of autocorrelation (Durbin-Watson test).

Model 3: sleep_latency ~ activeMinutes

  • R-squared: 0.002681
  • Significance: Insignificant Coefficient (p-value = 0.148).
  • Assumption Violations:
    • Normality of Residuals: Histogram and Shapiro-Wilk test confirm non-normality.
    • Independence of Residuals: Strong evidence of autocorrelation (Durbin-Watson test).

Model 4: TotalMinutesAsleep ~ activeMinutes

  • R-squared: 0.01018
  • Significance: Significant Coefficient (p-value = 0.023).
  • Assumption Violations:
    • Normality of Residuals: Shapiro-Wilk test suggests departure from normality.
    • Homoscedasticity: Evidence of heteroscedasticity (Breusch-Pagan test).
    • Independence of Residuals: Strong evidence of autocorrelation (Durbin-Watson test).

Model 5: sleep_latency ~ SedentaryMinutes

  • R-squared: 0.02514
  • Significance: Significant Coefficient (p-value = 0.000746).
  • Assumption Violations:
    • Linearity : The relationship does not appear strictly linear.
    • Normality of Residuals: Residuals do not follow a normal distribution.
    • Homoscedasticity: Evidence of heteroscedasticity (Breusch-Pagan test).

Model 6: TotalMinutesAsleep ~ SedentaryMinutes

  • R-squared: 0.3597
  • Significance: Significant Coefficient (p-value < 2.2e-16).
  • Assumption Violations:
    • Normality of Residuals: Shapiro-Wilk test suggests departure from normality.
    • Homoscedasticity: Evidence of heteroscedasticity (Breusch-Pagan test).
    • Independence of Residuals: Autocorrelation observed (Durbin-Watson test).

Comparison and Recommendations:

Model 6 is chosen as the best fit primarily due to its superior explanatory power as evidenced by its R-squared value, in the context where other models show similar characteristics regarding the significance and assumption checks.

  • Best Fit (Highest R-squared): Model 6 (TotalMinutesAsleep ~ SedentaryMinutes) has the highest R-squared (35.93%), indicating it explains the most variability in the dependent variable.

The aim is to refine this model through potential enhancements, which may involve adjustments, the inclusion of supplementary variables, or transformations. Influence of Acitivty (composite score) on Sleep Latency

Model 3 Fitting (sleep_latency ~ activeMinutes)

A decision has been made to construct a composite variable named ‘activity’ by utilizing a composite score derived from the standard MET ranges. This variable amalgamates multiple aspects of activity for enhanced analysis.

Composite Score for Activity Intensity

A composite score is calculated based on MET values (energy expenditure) for different activity levels. Weights are assigned to each activity level to reflect their importance in assessing intensity:

  • Very Active (Weight: 0.5): High-intensity activities (e.g., running)
  • Fairly Active (Weight: 0.3): Moderate-intensity activities (e.g., brisk walking)
  • Lightly Active (Weight: 0.2): Low-intensity activities (e.g., light housework)

The composite score is a weighted average of these MET values. Activities are categorized into intensity levels based on the composite score:

  • Low Intensity (Composite Score < 3.0)
  • Moderate Intensity (3.0 ≤ Composite Score < 6.0)
  • High Intensity (Composite Score ≥ 6.0)

The weights were chosen to reflect the relative importance of each activity level in assessing overall activity intensity.

# Define weights based on MET ranges
composite_score_weights <- c(weights <- c(0.5, 0.3, 0.2))  # VeryActive: 0.5, FairlyActive: 0.3, LightlyActive: 0.2

# Create the composite score (activeMinutes)
daily_data$activeMinutes <- 
  daily_data$VeryActiveMinutes * weights[1] +
  daily_data$FairlyActiveMinutes * weights[2] +
  daily_data$LightlyActiveMinutes * weights[3]

#Fit a linear regression model
lm_activity_latency <- lm(sleep_latency ~ activeMinutes, data = daily_data)

# Summarize the model

print(homoscedasticity_test_sedentary_duration)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  lm_sedentary_duration
## BP = 6.5474, df = 1, p-value = 0.0105
# 4.Perform Durbin-Watson test for Independence of Residuals
durbin_watson_test_sedentary_duration<- dwtest(lm_sedentary_duration)
print(durbin_watson_test_sedentary_duration)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  lm_sedentary_duration

Model 6 (TotalMinutesAsleep ~ SedentaryMinutes)

Addressing Model Shortcomings

Addressing Heteroskedasticity with Robust Regression

To mitigate the issue of heteroskedasticity while preserving the interpretability associated with Ordinary Least Squares (OLS), the choice is made to employ a robust regression model. This approach enhances the robustness of the analysis.

Implementing Robust Regression

Examining Autocorrelation in the Robust Model

Although addressing autocorrelation is not typically a primary concern in linear regression models, particularly with cross-sectional data, our initial analysis hinted at potential autocorrelation. Subsequently, we will assess the robust model to ascertain whether this concern has been effectively addressed.

# Extract and analyze residuals for autocorrelation
residuals_robust_sedentary_duration <- residuals(robust_model_sedentary_duration)
n <- length(residuals_robust_sedentary_duration)
d <- sum(diff(residuals_robust_sedentary_duration)^2)
durbin_watson_statistic <- d / sum(residuals_robust_sedentary_duration^2)

# Check for autocorrelation
if (durbin_watson_statistic < 1.5) {
  cat("Positive autocorrelation detected.\n")
} else if (durbin_watson_statistic > 2.5) {
  cat("Negative autocorrelation detected.\n")
} else {
  cat("No significant autocorrelation detected.\n")
}
## No significant autocorrelation detected.
# Display the Durbin-Watson statistic
durbin_watson_statistic
## [1] 1.632924

Key Findings from the Robust Regression Model

  • Impact of SedentaryMinutes: The model indicates that each additional minute of sedentary activity is associated with an average decrease of about 0.49053 minutes in TotalMinutesAsleep.
  • P-Value Interpretation: The p-value obtained for SedentaryMinutes, which is less than 2.2e-16, indicates a statistically significant inverse relationship with TotalMinutesAsleep. This suggests that as SedentaryMinutes increase, TotalMinutesAsleep tend to decrease, with a high level of confidence in this observed trend.
  • Model’s Explanatory Power: Model’s Explanatory Power Improvement: The updated model accounts for approximately 42.56% of the variance in TotalMinutesAsleep, which is a noticeable increase from the 35.97% explained by the previous model. This improvement in the R-squared value suggests that the updated model has a stronger fit to the data, capturing more of the variability in the dependent variable with its predictors.
  • Autocorrelation: No significant autocorrelation detected in the model’s residuals, indicating improved reliability.

Conclusion

The analysis reveals complex and individual variability in sleep patterns. It was observed that a substantial segment of the population achieves less than the recommended 7 hours of sleep, with approximately half of the recorded instances falling short of this benchmark. Additionally, a significant majority exhibit sleep latency over 20 minutes, pointing to prevalent sleep quality concerns. These insights underscore the necessity of implementing targeted measures to promote better sleep hygiene and extend sleep duration. Further sections will delineate comprehensive recommendations, advancing data-driven approaches to improve sleep health in the context of organizational well-being.

Recommendations for Stakeholders

User Engagement & Usage

  • Loyalty Programs for High Usage: Develop exclusive features or loyalty rewards for the 76% highly engaged users to sustain their interest.
  • Targeted Upselling: Offer premium services to the ‘High Usage’ group, capitalizing on their commitment.
  • Enhancing Moderate Usage Engagement: Identify barriers for the 21% ‘Moderate Usage’ group and address them with product improvements or tailored marketing.
  • Understanding Low Usage: Investigate the reasons behind the 3% ‘Low Usage’ group’s limited engagement for targeted interventions.
  • Retention and Growth: Focus on maintaining high user engagement and transitioning ‘Moderate’ users to ‘High Usage’.
  • Feedback-Informed Product Development: Encourage user feedback across all segments for continuous product enhancement.

Sleep Latency and Health

  • Products for Sleep Initiation: Develop solutions for the 66.7% with extended sleep latency, like relaxation aids or educational content on sleep hygiene.
  • Moderate Sleep Latency Interventions: Offer guidance or light sleep aids to the 20.8% with 10-20 minute sleep latency.
  • Sharing Best Practices: Utilize insights from the 12.5% with quick sleep onset to educate others.
  • Personalized Sleep Features: Implement advanced sleep tracking with personalized goals and educational content.
  • Relaxation Tools: Include guided meditation and calming soundscapes for better sleep preparation.
  • Sleep and Activity Analytics: Offer analytics on the correlation between physical activity and sleep quality.

Physical Activity & Sedentary Behavior

  • Active Lifestyle Promotion: Encourage physical activities to improve sleep quality, with goal setting and progress tracking.
  • Educational Outreach: Inform users about the positive impact of reduced sedentary behavior on sleep.

Communication & Motivation

  • Customized Messaging: Use motivational and data-driven messages to encourage active lifestyle choices and highlight their sleep benefits.
